{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"040758ef-972b-42bd-88d7-6e9c55b0bbec","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n### 1. Install the tool inside the pod\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n### 2. Find your process\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 3. Collect a trace (30s example)\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope**.\n\n### 4. Copy it out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>\n```\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, threadpool stats — useful to confirm the problem before collecting a full trace.\n\n### Tips\n- **`--profile cpu-sampling`** is lightweight and best for CPU-bound issues.\n- If you need OS-level context (kernel stacks), use **`dotnet-trace`** with `--format speedscope` or switch to **`perf`** (requires `SYS_PTRACE` / `privileged` container).\n- For production, consider `--duration` or `--buffersize` to limit overhead and file size.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1717cf66-03d7-4b14-9a89-24c5b6033731","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question - I don't need to search a codebase or run commands. I can answer from knowledge.","outputTokens":461,"requestId":"DA14:1169D4:2140823:24D6B7C:6A03D48A"},"id":"c048f52d-0300-48b8-9533-58c6e175360d","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:32:05.455Z","parentId":"367a05a9-2421-4dbd-941e-cec73cdc0631"}
